EXECUTE
  Run a script file through the client as a batch of commands.

SYNTAX
  execute <filename>
  exec    <filename>

DESCRIPTION
  Tells the client to open <filename> on the LOCAL (client) machine
  and feed each line back to the server as commands, one at a time.

  This lets you pre-write sequences of empire commands in a text file
  and run them all without typing each one interactively.

  The script file is a plain text file with one command per line.
  Blank lines and lines starting with '#' are ignored by the server
  (sent but produce "Unknown command").

  execute uses protocol message C_EXECUTE (id=12).  The C client
  handles this by opening the named file and reading from it.
  When the file ends, the client returns to normal interactive input.

SCRIPT FILE FORMAT
  One empire command per line, e.g.:

    # Set up food thresholds
    threshold food * 50
    threshold food 0,0 2000
    # Enlist some military
    enlist * 100
    census *

EXAMPLE
  execute /home/me/scripts/startup.emp
  execute ./my_country_setup.emp

NOTES
  The filename must be accessible on the CLIENT machine, not the server.
  Redirections inside scripts (>, >>) are not supported.
  To abort a running execute, press interrupt (Ctrl-C or equivalent).

